.
 In the equilibrium of the first best, A is equal to 0 for both types of
 agents.
 Utility for the principal is maximized at the point where the iso-utility
 convex function of the principal is tangent with the iso-utility function
 of the agent, i.e.
 the point such that 
\begin_inset Formula $t-\theta q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S(q)-t$
\end_inset

 is maximized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The second best
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Incentive compatibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
In the previous graph, one can observe that the utility of the good type
 is higher if she chooses the first best contract of the bad type rather
 than the contract that was destined for her.
 Therefore, the first best is not implementable if the type of the agent
 is not known to the principal.
 Under the second best, each type of agent must choose willingly the contract
 that is destined for him/her, so that the following incentive constraints
 (`IC') must be verified:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t_{H}-\theta_{H}q_{H} & \geq t_{L}-\theta_{H}q_{L}\tag{IC\ensuremath{_{H}}}\label{IC}\\
t_{L}-\theta_{L}q_{L} & \geq t_{H}-\theta_{L}q_{H}\tag{IC\ensuremath{_{L}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Under those conditions, type 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 chooses contract 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{H}$
\end_inset

 and type 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 chooses contract 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{L}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Participation constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
We must also have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t_{H}-\theta_{H}q_{H} & \geq0\tag{IR\ensuremath{_{H}}}\\
t_{L}-\theta_{L}q_{L} & \geq0\tag{IR\ensuremath{_{L}}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
if we want both types of agents to participate.
 Those are the individual rationality (`IR') constraints.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\size normal
\emph on
Notations:
\emph default
 Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{H}=t_{H}-\theta_{H}q_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{L}=t_{L}-\theta_{L}q_{L}$
\end_inset

 and denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta=\theta_{H}-\theta_{L}>0.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The program of the principal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
The program of the principal is then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\underset{t_{L},q_{L},t_{H},q_{H}}{\max} & v(S(q_{L})-t_{L})+(1-v)(S(q_{H})-t_{H})\\
 & \text{s.t.}\nonumber \\
U_{H} & \geq U_{L}-\Delta q_{L}\\
U_{L} & \geq U_{H}+\Delta q_{H}\\
U_{H} & \geq0\\
U_{L} & \geq0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
How can the program be solved? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\size normal
First, note that adding up the participation constraint for both types,
 one obtains:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{H}+U_{L}\geq U_{L}+U_{H}+\Delta(q_{H}-q_{L})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 which means that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q_{H}\leq q_{L}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The high type will produce less than the low type in the second best outcome.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\size normal
Second, note that if the participation constraint on type 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is verified and the incentive constraint for type 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is verified, then the participation constraint for type 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is verified.
 The participation constraint for type 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is thus superfluous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\size normal
Third, suppose now the incentive constraint for type 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is binding.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{L}=U_{H}+\Delta q_{H},$
\end_inset

 which, translated into the incentive constraint for type 
\begin_inset Formula $L,$
\end_inset

 means I must have 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{H}\geq U_{H}+\Delta(q_{H}-q_{L}),$
\end_inset

 which is always the case as 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{H}\leq q_{L}.$
\end_inset

 Therefore, the incentive constraint for type 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is also superfluous.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
From this, I can conclude that the participation constraint for the high
 type will be binding (
\begin_inset Formula $U_{H}=0$
\end_inset

) while the incentive constraint for the low type will be binding (
\begin_inset Formula $U_{L}=\Delta q_{H}$
\end_inset

).
 This ensures all constraints are verified while minimizing the rent given
 out to each type.
 Taking the two above inequalities and replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{L}$
\end_inset

 by their expression in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{H},$
\end_inset

 the program of the principal can thus be simplified into:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{q_{H},q_{L}}{\max}v(S(q_{L})-\theta_{L}q_{L})+(1-v)(S(q_{H})-\theta_{H}q_{H})-v\Delta q_{H}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Maximizing the above with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{H}$
\end_inset

 one obtains
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S^{\prime}(q_{L})=\theta_{L}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S^{\prime}(q_{H})=\theta_{H}+\frac{v}{1-v}\Delta
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Note how the result is distorted compared to the first best maximization
 program: There is no distortion for the good type who will produce the
 same as in the first best, while the bad type will produce less than in
 the first best.
