\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{q_{H},t_{H},q_{L},t_{L}}{\max}V=p_{1}(S(q_{H})-t_{H})+(1-p_{1})(S(q_{L})-t_{L})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{ s.t. }p_{1}u(t_{H})+(1-p_{1})u(t_{L})-\psi\geq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
if he wants the agent to exert effort (the constraint ensures the agent's
 ex-post anticipated utility from accepting the contract and exerting effort
 is positive), and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{q_{H},t_{H},q_{L},t_{L}}{\max}V=p_{0}(S(q_{H})-t_{H})+(1-p_{0})(S(q_{L})-t_{L})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\text{s.t. }p_{0}u(t_{H})+(1-p_{0})u(t_{L}) & \geq & 0
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
if instead the principal wants the agent to exert no effort (this can happen
 if compensating for a high effort is too expensive).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
If effort is desired, and denoting 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 the Lagrange multiplier, the Lagrangian can be written:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{c}
L=p_{1}(S(q_{H})-t_{H})+(1-p_{1})(S(q_{L})-t_{L})\\
+\lambda[p_{1}u(t_{H})+(1-p_{1})u(t_{L})]
\end{array}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Maximizing with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{L}$
\end_inset

, one obtains:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
-p_{1}+\lambda p_{1}u^{\prime}(t_{H}^{\ast}) & =0\\
-(1-p_{1})+\lambda(1-p_{1})u^{\prime}(t_{L}^{\ast}) & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{H}^{\ast}=t_{L}^{\ast}\equiv t_{1}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 is set such that the agent gets 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 utility so 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t_{1}^{\ast})=\psi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
The same result is obtained if the principal chooses not to induce effort,
 but 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t_{0}^{\ast})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
The principal will chooses to induce effort only if:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
