\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The second best outcome
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Suppose the agent has infinite wealth, so any 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{L}$
\end_inset

 (punishment in case of bad outcome) can be asked for.
 Suppose also the principal cannot observe the agent's effort or equivalently,
 that he cannot prove effort was low.
 Then the agent must be induced to choose the desired level of effort, so
 incentive constraints must be verified as well as participation constraints.
 Suppose high effort is desired.
 The agent's incentive constraint is then such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}u(t_{H})+(1-p_{1})u(t_{L})-\psi\geq p_{0}u(t_{H})+(1-p_{0})u(t_{L})
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
and the participation constraint is such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}u(t_{H})+(1-p_{1})u(t_{L})-\psi\geq0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Suppose for simplicity that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(t)=t$
\end_inset

 (the agent is risk neutral).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
Solving the principal's maximisation program, the two constraints (Incentive
 and Participation) will be binding.
 This gives a system of two equalities with two unknown,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p_{1}t_{H}+(1-p_{1})t_{L}-\psi & =p_{0}t_{H}+(1-p_{0})t_{L}\\
p_{1}t_{H}+(1-p_{1})t_{L}-\psi & =0
\end{align}

\end_inset

 which has an unique solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
t_{L}^{\ast} & =-\frac{p_{0}\psi}{p_{1}-p_{0}}\\
t_{H}^{\ast} & =\frac{(1-p_{0})\psi}{p_{1}-p_{0}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

 So the expected payment for the principal is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p_{1}t_{H}^{\ast}+(1-p_{1})t_{L}^{\ast}=\psi
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size normal
This is the same as would be paid if effort was observable, i.e.
 the principal merely compensates the agent for her effort.
 One would also see that the same expected payment (
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

